{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516809","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516809"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:47:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:47:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12721"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12721","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12721"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.04,0.1,0.32,0.52]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5176"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103590"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5176","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5176"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12721"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86007"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"92"},{"type":"tags","id":"1217"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8766"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8787"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15945"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36838"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103590","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103590"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old Asian man with chronic Hepatitis B virus infection is being treated in hospital. His doctors are concerned about his risk of developing hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC). His liver function tests show ALT 30 U/L (5-40), AST 28 U/L (5-40), ALP 70 U/L (30-120), GGT 35 U/L (5-50), total bilirubin 12 \u00b5mol/L (3-20), and albumin 40 g/L (35-50). His Fibroscan is consistent with no fibrosis or cirrhosis. He has no history of alcohol abuse or other liver diseases.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate method for HCC surveillance in this individual?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["MRI 12-monthly","CT scan 6-monthly","Alpha-fetoprotein 12-monthly","Ultrasound 6-monthly","Ultrasound and alpha-fetoprotein 12-monthly"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EChronic hepatitis B virus (HBV) infection is a significant risk factor for developing hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC), particularly in Asian populations. The risk of developing HCC is highest in individuals with underlying cirrhosis, but even those without cirrhosis can develop HCC, especially with underlying HBV infection. According to the guidelines, all patients with cirrhosis should undergo surveillance testing and the following patients without cirrhosis but with HBV infection should undergo surveillance every 6 months for HCC:\u003Cbr /\u003E1. Asian men \u0026gt;40 years\u003Cbr /\u003E2. Asian women \u0026gt;50 years\u003Cbr /\u003E3. Sub-Saharan Africans \u0026gt;20 years\u003Cbr /\u003E4. Indigenous \u0026amp; Torres Strait Islanders \u0026gt;50 years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe appropriate surveillance method for diagnosing HCC in high-risk individuals is \u003Cstrong\u003Eultrasound 6-monthly\u003C/strong\u003E. This surveillance strategy is recommended by current guidelines for individuals with chronic HBV infection without cirrhosis. Ultrasound is a safe and non-invasive imaging modality that can detect small HCC lesions. This mode of surveillance may be combined with alpha-fetoprotein (AFP) measurement, however this is not a firm recommendation in guidelines, as while AFP can further increase sensitivity it can also lead to higher false positives.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI 12-monthly\u003C/strong\u003E can be an effective option for the surveillance of HCC, but it is not recommended for surveillance purposes due to the high cost involved also the time period of 12 months is long enough for HCC to grow in considerable size and cause aggressive disease that might be difficult to control, so a cheap, non-invasive method at shorter intervals is recommended.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT scan 6-monthly\u003C/strong\u003E can also be very sensitive and specific for detecting even smaller hepatic lesions, but it is not recommended as a surveillance option because of the cost involved and the risk of high radiation involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAFP 12-monthly\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended. Even though AFP is a serum tumour marker for HCC, it is secreted by only approximately 50% of small HCC\u00a0lesions, and may be normal even in the setting of advanced disease. Moreover, the time period of 12 months is not appropriate for surveillance of HCC.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound and AFP 12-monthly\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended due to the issues around AFP specificity described previously and because the time period is too lengthy, which can lead to the tumour growing to a considerable size before being detected.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ultrasound 6 monthly is the appropriate surveillance method for diagnosing HCC in individuals with chronic HBV infection without cirrhosis."],"references":["Lubel, J.S., Strasser, S.I., Thompson, A.J., Cowie, B.C., MacLachlan, J., Allard, N.L., Holmes, J., Kemp, W.W., Majumdar, A., Iser, D., Howell, J. and Matthews, G.V. (2022), Australian consensus recommendations for the management of hepatitis B. Med J Aust, 216: 478-486. Available at: https://doi.org/10.5694/mja2.51430"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86007"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12721"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia"